     section "configuration" below.


     2.1   Command line arguments
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     PNTCHK understands a few command line arguments described here.
     It always needs one of the following arguments:
     - "-S" and the file name, optionally containing wildcard ("?" or "*")
       This option defines the name(s) of the segment file(s) to be
       checked.
     - "-L"
       By this PNTCHK starts compilation of pointlist from the
       segments contained in the MASTER directory (see below);
       the search for the segments PNTCHK performs without assistance.

     The following argument can be given additionally:
     - "-C" and file name (without space)
       Defines the configuration file name, other than .\PNTCHK.CTL


     3.  Configuration
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     In PNTCHK there are some adjustments that are absolutely necessary
     as well as some that are really only needed in some unusual cases.
     If you want to change anything you first should know how PNTCHK
     works.


     3.1  How PNTCHK works
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     The main part of PNTCHK is the module checking the validity of
     incomming segments. It is executed both in "-S"-mode of PNTCHK
     and when pointlist is being compiled ("-L"-mode), for every
     segment to be included into the pointlist.
     Thus almost all the rules applied when the segments are checked in
     "-S"-mode are also applicable in the "-L"-mode.


     3.1.1  The mode checking the validity of segments "-S".
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     This mode is base in operation of the program. PNTCHK gets the name
     of the segment (or segments if the willcard is given) for processing
     from the command line. The name of the segment(s) can be both absolute
     (concerning root directory), and relative (concerning the current
     directory).

     The name (the number) of the sender of a segment PNTCHK gets from
     the name of the segment. How it is done depends on the value of
     configuration variable SEGMENTFORMAT. Several formats are supported
     at once. The zone and network numbers are got from the ADDRESS switch.

     Further the nodelist is scanned. This unit is started only in the case
     if the variable NODELIST refers to valid nodelist (if it is not commented
     out and if the file to which refers NODELIST, exists). Depending on the
     status of the bossnode in the nodelist (and appropriate customization of
     variables ABSENDPOINTS, NORMALPOINTS, HUBPOINTS, HOLDPOINTS, DOWNPOINTS)
     the segment will be or will not be processed. Nodelist is scanned and
     its index file is created. In the further operation goes with this index
     file until the nodelist vary. As the nodelist it is possible to set
     both a local network segment, and zone and even world nodelist. In the
     latter case search of an appropriate network segment will be made in
     the body of nodelist.

     First check of a segment as a whole is performed - check on valid age
     of a segment (variables SEGWRNAGE and SEGERRAGE), on correctness of
     layout of commentlines and their quantity (BETWEENCOMMENTS,
     COMMENTCOUNT). After that the segment is read line by line and each
     string is tested separately.

     Before processing of a segment it is possible to copy it into
     special back-up directory (set by variable BACKUPDIR).

     At the end of operation, depending on whether errors in a segment were
     found or not, the segment is transferred to the appropriate
     directory. Warnings are not considered for errors. At absence
     of errors the segment is considered correct and is transferred
     into MASTER directory, otherwise is transferred to BAD directory
     or is deleted (variable KILLBAD).

     Checker dispatches the reports about its operation to the
     remailer of a segment. In case of the retrieved errors (warnings) the
     message-report on them is also sent. According to your desire the
     error report can be carbon-copied to you (variable COORDINATOR in
     the configuration file). Message reports are created in the *.MSG-format
     in NETMAIL directory defined by you. Attributes of letters are set
     by a configuration variable ATTRIBUTES.

     At sending message reports template files are very widely used,
     which you can edit to own taste, for example, translate them to
     Russian. In template files it is possible to set macros,
     which at sending the report will be replaced with value appropriate
     to them at present.

     Operation of PNTCHK is completed with various exit codes (errorlevels),
     depending on presence of errors (see chapter 3.4 of the present
     manual).


     3.1.2  Pointlist compilation mode "-L".
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     This mode requires no additional command line switches. By this PNTCHK
     scans the MASTER directory and finds in increasing order the segments
     corresponding the masks defined by SEGMENTFORMAT variables.
     Every found segment is checked in the way depending on the
     CREATIONCHECK variable (can be checked like in "-S"-mode or less
     careful, see below). If the segment is correct, no report is sent
     to the bossnode (unlike in "-S"-mode, where the report is sent in
     any case). Only reports about errors (if any) are sent. The
     template pntlst.tpl is used instead of error.tpl.


     3.2    The configuration file
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     In the configuration file (PNTCHK.CTL default) various parameters
     are set that fix how the program works. This file can be edited with
     any ASCII editor. Empty lines and lines beginning with a
     semicolon (";") will be ignored. Maximum length of a string is
     97 characters (16 characters per a variable and 80 characters for
     its value).


     3.2.1  Sample file
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     [...]


     3.2.2  System section
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     3.2.2.1  Variable: ADDRESS
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: ADDRESS <zone>:<net>/<node>[.<point>]

     This variable defines the address of your system. This is one
     of the most important variables, the value of which is used in
     several ways:
     - as the address of the sender of the outgoing report-messages;
     - the host part of it is used by nodelist processing routine,
       and when checking the strings "Boss,*" in the segments.


     3.2.2.2  Variable: NETMAIL
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: NETMAIL [<path>\]<directory>

     This variable defines the path to your netmail-directory, where
     message reports are created.

     You can define both absolute, and relative path to the directory,
     including beginning with "\" (root directory).

     Examples: NETMAIL C:\MAIL\NETMAIL\
                       NETMAIL .\MAIL
                       NETMAIL MSGS
                       NETMAIL \MAIl\MSG\

     If not defined, no reports will be sent.


     3.2.2.3  Variable: MASTER
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: MASTER [<path>\]<directory>

     This variable defines the path to the so called MASTER directory.

     The MASTER directory is the place where correct segments are placed.
     It is used in two situations. First of all, in the "-S"-mode of
     PNTCHK here are moved correct segments after checks. Second, in the
     "-L"-mode this directory is scanned for segments to be included
     into new pointlist.

     As in case of NETMAIL directory, you can define both absolute, and
     relative path to the directory, including beginning with "\" (root
     directory).

     See the examples to NETMAIL variable.

     Preset: . (current directory: the segment is not moved)


     3.2.2.4  Variable: BADFILES
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: BADFILES [<path>\]<directory>

     This variable defines the path and the name of the directory, where
     incorrect segments are placed.

     See the examples to NETMAIL variable.

     Preset: . (current directory: the segment is not moved)

     Also see the KILLBAD variable (below).


     3.2.2.5  Variable: BACKUPDIR
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: BACKUPDIR [<path>\]<directory>

     Sometimes it is useful to save the copy of incomming segment before
     it is checked by PNTCHK. During the process of checking the segment
     can be modified (eg., superfluous comment lines are removed,
     incorrect values of SYSOP, BAUD, LOCATION etc. fields are changed
     (see COMMENTCOUNT, CHANGELOCATION, CHANGESYSOP etc. variablees, below)),
     but due to incorrect config adjustments or due to system crash can
     be not as expected.

     Although the real possibility of such abnormal situation is quite
     low, you can always safe yourself by defining BACKUPDIR variable.
     The segments will be copied into BACKUPDIR both in the "-S"-mode
     and in the "-L"-mode (when variable CREATIONCHECK=FULL, see below).

     See the examples to NETMAIL variable.

     When not defined, the segments are not saved.


     3.2.2.6  Variable: TEMPDIR
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: TEMPDIR [<path>\]<directory>

     Working directory, needed by PNTCHK to place there temporary files.

     If after crash in this directory some temporary files are
     left, they can be used to recover lost data. If the crash caused
     by the bug in the PNTCHK itself, include the description of
     left temporary files into the bugreport.

     See the examples to NETMAIL variable.

     Preset: . (current directory)


     3.2.2.7  Variable: TEMPLATEPATH
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: TEMPLATEPATH [<path>\]<directory>

     This variable sets the path where allocate file templates for
     message reports of checker. The given directory is set parallelly
     to the current, that is the template files indicated without path or
     indicated with relative path, are searched in the current directory
     and in the directory set by TEMPLATEPATH.
     You always can reassign path to concrete template, having set its name
     with absolute path.

     Examples see in the description to variable NETMAIL.

     Preset:. (the current directory)


     3.2.2.8  Variable: LOGFILE
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: LOGFILE [<path>\]<filename>

     The given variable allows to set a name of the logfile in
     which checker writes the report on made operations. If the path is not
     given, the file is created in the current directory.

     An example of usage: LOGFILE F:\MAIL\LOGS\mylog.txt

     Preset: PNTCHK.LOG


     3.2.2.9  Variable: LOGLEVEL
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: LOGLEVEL <tag>[<tag>[<tag>[<tag>...]]]

     Each message in the logfile starts with the defined character - tag.
     Tags are separated into groups on semantic load:

       + - the configuration information, parameters of the command line
       @ - current messages (on opening files, copying etc)
       & - operation with nodelist file
       [ - operation with template files
       # - detected errors in the segment
       { - operation with netmail
       <,> - carry of the segment
       | - other

     You can prohibit output of the defined groups of messages in
     the logfile. For this purpose it is simple enough to specify tags
     of appropriate groups in the variable LOGLEVEL.

     An example of usage: LOGLEVEL @|[

     Default value: no tags


     3.2.2.10  Variable: SHARINGMODE
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Variable: SHARINGMODE YES | NO

     This variable determines the way of addition of messages in the
     logfile. By default addition of messages is made through the buffer
     after its filling, that accelerates operation of the program
     a little, and also reduces number of disk operations. However it
     results to that in case of failure the part of messages appears
     lost.
     You can change a way of addition of messages in the logfile, having
     specified the program to close the logfile after each added
     line (having set the value of SHARINGMODE to YES).

     Default value: NO


     3.2.2.11  Variable: LITE
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: LITE YES | NO

     Variable switches on so called lite-mode of PNTCHK, which serves
     the local check of the pointlist segment before sending it to the
     coordinator.

     For more details, see the chapter 5 of this manual.

     Example of usage: LITE YES

     Default value: NO


     3.2.3  Message settings
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     3.2.3.1  Variable: FROM
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: FROM <fromname>

     Name of the remailer of message reports. Direct indication, and usage
     of macros (see bellow) are both allowed.

     Examples of usage: FROM Pavel Osi‡ov
                        FROM @owner
                        FROM @name‡rog, v@version

     Default value: @name‡rog 


     3.2.3.2  Variable: TO
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: TO <toname>

     Name of the receiver of message reports.
 
     Example: TO @FirstSysO‡Name @LastSysO‡Name

     Default value: SysO‡


     3.2.3.3  Variable: SUBJECT
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: SUBJECT <subject>

     The subject of message reports.

     Example: SUBJECT segment: @segname, @seglength bytes, dated @segdate

     Defaule value: @nameprog report


     3.2.3.4  Variable: TEARLINE
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: TEARLINE <tearline>

     Tearline of message reports.

     Example: TEARLINE @nameprog, R: @owner (@serial)

     By default empty.


     3.2.3.5  Variable: ORIGIN
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: ORIGIN <origin>

     Origin of message reports.

     By default empty.


     3.2.3.6  Variable: ATTRIBUTES
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: ATTRIBUTES <attr> [<attr> [<attr> [<attr> ...]]]

     This variable allows to set attributes of the report messages. All
     attributes hardly will be necessary for you, except for the most
     widespread (PVT, LOC, K/S), nevertheless PNTCHK allows to define
     almost all possible attributes.

     Possible attributes are:

     PVT - ‡rivat, the letter is private (standard attribute
           for netmail-messages)
     CRA - crash, urgent letter
     RCV - received, the letter is obtained
     SNT - sent, the letter is transmitted
     ATT - attach, the letter contains file attached to it
     TRS - transit, transit letter
     ORP - orphan, erratic letter
     K/S - kill/sent, delete the letter after sending
     LOC - local, the letter is local
     HLD - hold, to hold back the letter until the receiver takes away it
           from our system
     FRQ - freq, the letter contains file request
     RRQ - return receipt request, request about obtaining of
           the notice on delivery
     RRC - return receipt, the letter is the notice on delivery
     ARQ - audit request, request about passing of the letter through
           transit sites
     URQ - file update request, request of the refreshed version of the
           file

     Default: PVT LOC 


     3.2.3.7  Variable: ONLYONEREPORT
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: ONLYONEREPORT YES | NO

     After check of a segment in the '-S'-mode the checker dispatches the
     report on the done operation. The report can consist of one or two
     letters. The former letter is the general report about the done
     operation (the content is got from NORMALTEMPLATE). The latter contains
     the report on errors if they are available (ERRORTEMPLATE).
     However, if such situation with reports does not arrange you, you
     can set value of ONLYONEREPORT in YES, therefore checker always will
     dispatch only one message report: NORMALTEMPLATE in case of correct
     segment, and ERRORTEMPLATE (and only it) in case of detection of
     errors in the segment.

     An example: ONLYONEREPORT YES

     Default: NO


     3.2.3.8  Variable: COORDINATOR
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: COORDINATOR <address> [<Coordinator's name>]

     The address and the name (if not defined, "Coordinator" is used) of
     receiver of copies of the error messages, sent to segments remailers.

     By default backup of messages does not occur.


     3.2.4  Nodelist settings
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     In this section operation of the checker with nodelist is defined -
     its name and its place, the name of the nodelist index, segments of
     nodes with what status should be included in the nodelist, and whether
     it is necessary in general to check the nodelist.


     3.2.4.1  Variable: NODELIST
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: NODELIST [<path>\]<filename>.<extension>

     This variable defines the path and the name of the nodelist. It is
     possible to specify a direct name of the concrete file ord to specify
     a mask according to which the search for available nodelist is performed. 

     The mask is allowed only in the extension and only of two types:
       * - search of the nodelist any extension, both with digital, and
           with text will be made.
           If the directory contains some nodelist files with the names
           matching the search criteria, the nodelist with the last date
           of creation will be taken.
           WARNING! Be careful! Check on the nodelist file for its
           "quality" is not made. The situation when in the nodelist
           directory there is the archived nodelist file having later date
           of creation (eg., you have created the nodelist, and then have
           packed it with the same name) is quite possible.
           The checker will try to process this archive file, and,
           naturally, will produce an error. It is necessary for you
           to take care of inadmissibility of occurrence of such situation.

      999 - such extension is a mask, i.e. will be searched not only
           nodelist file with .999 extension (I think, it is not so terrible
           for hardly someone will have necessity of storage and the more
           so processings nodelist with such name). In this case it will be
           searched for nodelist file containing in the extension only
           digits. That is NODELIST.103 will be processed, but N5020.NDL
           and NODELIST.13A not.

     Examples of usage: NODELIST net5020.ndl
                        NODELIST z2-list.192
                        NODELIST c:\mail\brake\nodelist\nodelist.999
                        NODELIST ndl5020.*

     If variable NODELIST is not defined, search for nodelist and check
     on existence of the bossnode is not performed.


     3.2.4.2  Variable: NDLINDEX
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: NDLINDEX [<path>\]<filename>

     This variable defines the filename of nodelist index. If a new
     nodelist is detected, its index is compiled in the file defined
     by NDLINDEX variable. In the further operation goes only with the index,
     that essentially accelerates operation with the nodelist, and its
     recompillance occurs only at appearance of a new nodelist.

     WARNING!!! Be cautious and ... watch that the name of the index
     not coincided with a name of the nodelist. Consequences can be
     unpredictable.

     Example of usage: NDLINDEX PNTCHECK.NDL

     Default value: PNTCHK.NDL


     3.2.4.3  Variables: ABSENTPOINTS, DOWNPOINTS, HOLDPOINTS,
                        HUBPOINTS, NORMALPOINTS, PVTPOINTS
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: ABSENTPOINTS YES | NO | NOSEND
             DOWNPOINTS YES | NO | NOSEND
             HOLDPOINTS YES | NO | NOSEND
             HUBPOINTS YES | NO | NOSEND
             NORMALPOINTS YES | NO | NOSEND
             PVTPOINTS YES | NO | NOSEND

     This variablees determine the status of nodes, the segments of which
     should be included into the pointlist. That is for segments of each
     group of bossnodes it is possible to resolve or prohibit entry in
     pointlist.
     Such groups are:
        HUB - hub
        NORMAL - ordinary node
        PVT - privat node (PVT prefix)
        HOLD - node with HOLD prefix
        DOWN - node with DOWN prefix
        ABSENT - node absent in the nodelist

     Thus, you can eliminate from the pointlist segments, for example, of
     absent nodes and nodes with status HOLD and DOWN, or, on the contrary,
     to create pointlist only from segments of hubs.

     The values NO and NOSEND are identical in their functioning with one
     exception: in the former case the remailer of the segment will
     receive a report message from checker concerning the problem with
     his segment. In the latter case the segment is rejected silently.

     Example of usage: ABSENTPOINTS NOSEND
                       DOWNPOINTS NOSEND
                       HOLDPOINTS NO
                       HUBPOINTS YES
                       NORMALPOINTS YES
                       PVTPOINTS YES

     Defaults: to include into pointlist segments of all nodes
               (all variablees in YES)


     3.2.5  General segment check variablees
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     3.2.5.1  Variable: SEGMENTFORMAT
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: SEGMENTFORMAT (<?>|~D|~H)(<?>|~D|~H)...(<?>|~D|~H)

     Syntax: SEGMENTFORMAT (<?>|~D|~H)(<?>|~D|~H)...(<?>|~D|~H)

     This variable sets the format (mask) of a segment transmitted to
     the program, that is actually in what place of the name of the segment
     to search for the digital combination having the number of the
     node - sender of the segment. Value SEGMENTFORMAT consists of
     combinations of characters, each of which corresponds to one
     character of the name of the segment. The number of combinations of a
     mask and characters of a name of a segment should be equal. To the given
     combinations of characters concern:

     <any_char> - any character; this character is not significant for the
          program and is put only to determine real location of the
          following behind it of significant combinations. Hence, 
          'A characters, 'B', '?' in a mask are handled absolutely
          equally (as against a mask, e.g., in variables LOCATION, FLAGS
          etc) and mean " on this place there can be ANY CHARACTER ".
     ~D - the given combination is significant and determines location
          of decimal digit (0. 9), i.e. " On this place there can be any
          decimal digit which then is used for calculation of the address
          of the remailer of a segment "
     ~H - the given combination determines location of sexadecimal
          digit (0. F)

     Calculation of the address is made on formation rules decimal numbers,
     i.e., having X X X X X X X X X X X, we receive
     result X1 + 10*X2 + 100*X3 + 1000*X4 +... + 10000000000*X11
     This rule operates both in the ratio to decimal, and in the ratio to
     sexadecimal numbers, i.e. expression ~H~H~H at all does not mean
     three-value sexadecimal number, and means a decimal number, obtained
     addition of the bits multiplied on 10 in appropriate degree, let even
     bit and contains sexadecimal digit. E.g., a name of segment PAV33A78.TXT
     at mask? A % ~ H~H~H~H~H.*C! It will be recognized as
     8*1 + 7*10 + 10*100 + 3*1000 + + 3*10000 = 34078, 
     at mask? A % ~ D~D~D~D~D.*C! The error message will be obtained.

     You can define up to 10 variables SEGMENTFORMAT specifying different
     formats of a name of a segment.

     The note: the rule about equality of processing of combinations " any
     character " has one exception: if value RENAMESEGMENT (see below)
     equally YES. In this case in value of the _FIRST_ SEGMENTFORMAT should
     not contain the illegal characters prohibited OS for a name of a
     segment. Otherwise renaming of a segment becomes impossible.

     Examples of usage:
       SEGMENTFORMAT SEG~D~D~D~D~D.PNT
       SEGMENTFORMAT MOPOINTS.~H~D~D
       SEGMENTFORMAT ????????.~H~D~D  (the last two variants are absolutely
                                      identical in processing)

     The default is impossible (for operation checker one variable
     SEGMENTFORMAT) should be given even.


     3.2.5.2  Variable: RENAMESEGMENT
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: RENAMESEGMENT YES | NO

     The variable determines, whether it is necessary to put all names
     of the segments stored in base (in MASTER directory) into one format,
     if there are several formats defined (several variablees SEGMENTFORMAT
     defined). The segments are renamed to to the format defined by the
     first SEGMENTFORMAT variable.

     An example of usage: RENAMESEGMENT YES

     Default: NO


     3.2.5.3  Variable: KILLBAD
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: KILLBAD ALWAYS | YES | IFGOOD | NEVER | NO

     This variable determines the reaction of the program to segments
     containing errors. First, it determines, whether it is necessary to
     transfer incorrect segments into defined by BADFILES variable (see
     above) directory. Second, KILLBAD determines, whether it is
     necessary to search for and delete of old incorrect segments
     in case of obtaining a correct segment from the given bossnode.
     
     At obtaining an incorrect segment its further destiny is defined
     with value KILLBAD. If it is equal ALWAYS (synonym YES) the segment
     after processing will be simply deleted and will not be transferred
     anywhere. Otherwise the segment will be transferred in the directory
     defined by BADFILES, or remain in the current directory if the value
     of BADFILES is not defined.

     At obtaining a correct segment possibility of deleting of old
     incorrect segments can be included. Such deleting is made, if value
     KILLBAD is equal ALWAYS (YES) or IFGOOD. The new segment is transferred
     in MASTER then BADFILES is scanned and all retrieved old segments from
     the given bossnode are deleted.
     Comment: the segment, as a rule, will be one (or there will be no
     segment at all). Nevertheless hypothetically in BADFILES there can
     be several segments from one bossnode, satisfying miscellaneous
     SEGMENTFORMAT (the description of variable SEGMENTFORMAT see below).
     Such can take place, for example, on change of the format of sending
     segments in the network on solution of the coordinator or if in the
     network several formats are are officially supported and sysops
     themselves select, in what format to send segments. In any case
     PNTCHK provides such case, all old segments from the given bossnode,
     satisfying all SEGMENTFORMAT therefore will be removed.

     So, as the resume we shall mark, that three variants of behaviour of
     the program in the ratio to incorrect segments exist:
         ALWAYS or YES (synonyms) - to kill bad segments at their
             processing and to not transfer them to BADFILES
             directory,
             at obtaining a correct segment to scan and clean BADFILES
         IFGOOD - to transfer incorrect segments into BADFILES,
             at obtaining a correct segment to clean BADFILES
         NEVER (NO) - to transfer incorrect segments into BADFILES;
             at obtaining a correct segment not to clean BADFILES

     Examples of usage: KILLBAD ALWAYS
                        KILLBAD NO

     Default: NO


     3.2.5.4  Variable: SEGWRNAGE
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: SEGWRNAGE <age_in_days>

     The variable sets valid age of a segment (in days) at which
     exceeding to the remailer of a segment the reminder on necessity to
     resend the segment will be dispatched (template of the reminder is
     defined by AGEWRNTPL).

     Example of usage: SEGWRNAGE 365

     By default check is not performed.


     3.2.5.5  Variable: SEGERRAGE
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: SEGERRAGE <age_in_days>

     The variable sets valid age of a segment (in days) at which exceeding
     the segment is considered erratic and is not handled. The report template
     is set by AGEERRTPL variable.

     Example of usage: SEGERRAGE 730

     By default check is not done.


     3.2.5.6  Variable: TOUCHSEGMENTS
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: TOUCHSEGMENTS YES | NO

     Variable determines, whether to change the date of incomming
     segments to the current on receiving of them.
     This variable influences to the process of the check for valid age
     of the segments (variables SEGWRNAGE ® SEGERRAGE), setting the moment
     since which the age of the segments should be calculated:
     NO  - the date of the segment is not changed and, accordingly, the
           age of it is calculated since the moment of its creation at
           the node-sender,
     YES - the date of the segment is changed to the current and in the
           future the age of the segment is calculted from this point
           during checks

     Example of usage: TOUCHSEGMENTS YES

     Default value: NO


     3.2.5.7  Variable: COMMENTCOUNT
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: COMMENTCOUNT <count>

     Maximum number of lines of the segment containing the comments. At
     exceeding valid number PNTCHK cuts superfluous lines with comments
     with sending appropriate warning to the remailer of a segment.

     Example of usage: COMMENTCOUNT 5

     Default: 5


     3.2.5.8  Variable: BETWEENCOMMENTS
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: BETWEENCOMMENTS YES | NO

     The variable determines, whether comments not only in the beginning of
     a segment, but also between data lines are admitted. Even in case of
     the value set to YES, the total number of lines with comments (variable
     COMMENTCOUNT) all the same is checked.

     WARNING!!! If value is YES, do not overlook to correct CMNTERRTPL in
     appropriate way.

     Example of usage: BETWEENCOMMENTS NO

     Default: NO


     3.2.6  Proceeding of strings in segment
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     3.2.6.1  Variable: ADMISSIBLECHARS
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: ADMISSIBLECHARS <char>[ <char>[ ...] | \[<char>-<char>\]]

     This variable defines correct chars for pointlist strings. Chars or
     ranges of chars (in square brackets) are listed with space separator.

     Example of usage: ADMISSIBLECHARS [!-] [Ä-Ø] ‡ · [‚„‰ÂÊÁ] [Ë-Ô]

     Default value: [!-]


     3.2.6.2  Variable: CHECKCOMMENTS
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: CHECKCOMMENTS YES | NO

     This variable switches on the check on the comment lines for
     inadmissible characters (as inadmissible in the comment lines are
     treated so called "control characters" - the chars with the codes
     below #32).
     I recommend to switch this check on since the presence in the lines
     of the pointlist of control characters may lead to errors during
     their processing by the diff-processors and nodelist-compilers.

     Example of usage: CHECKCOMMENTS NO

     Default value: YES


     3.2.6.3  Variable: NODELIFECOMPAT
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: NODELIFECOMPAT YES | NO

     The variable switches on the compatibility mode with the popular
     diff-processor Nodelife, prohibiting comment lines, containing
     the character string ";`", which is inproperly processed by this
     diff-processor.
     Although the technical standarts do not provide for the ban of the
     above mentioned character string, I introduced such a variable by
     numerous requests of PNTCHK users due to wide distribution of
     Nodelife.

     Example of usage: NODELIFECOMPAT YES

     Default value: NO


     3.2.6.4  Variable: PREFIX
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: PREFIX <prefix> | @

     The variable allows to change the value of admissible Point-prefix
     of the pointlist line. To define an empty prefix use the mask @.

     Examples of usage: PREFIX Point
                        PREFIX @

     Default value: Point


     3.2.6.5  Variable: BAUD
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: BAUD <baud> [<baud> [<baud> ...]]

     Correct values for "modem speed" field.

     Example of usage: BAUD 9600 14400 21600 33600

     Default value: 300 1200 2400 9600


     3.2.6.6  Variable: LOCATION
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: LOCATION <location>

     Correct values for "system location" field. You may use masks here.

     You may define up to 255 LOCATION variables, defining different valid
