     3.2.6.7  Variable: PHONENUMBER
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: PHONENUMBER <number>

     Correct values for "phonenumber" field. You may use masks here.

     You may define up to 10 PHONENUMBER variables, defining different valid
     formats for telephone numbers.

     Example of usage: PHONENUMBER -Unpublished-
                       PHONENUMBER 7-095-???-????

     Default value: "-Unpublished-"


     3.2.6.8  Variable: SYSOP
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: SYSOP <SysOp_name>

     Correct values for "SysOp name" field. You may use masks here.

     You may define up to 20 SYSOP variables, defining different valid
     formats for system operator's name.

     Example of usage: SYSOP * !@
                       SYSOP * !*[Nn][Oo]_[Nn][Aa][Mm][Ee]*

     Default value: "*"


     3.2.6.9  Variable: SYSTEM
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: SYSTEM <system_name>

     Valid values of a field "system name". Masks can be used.

     You can define up to 20 variables, specifying different valid formats
     of system names.

     Examples of usage: SYSTEM * !@
                        SYSTEM * !*[Nn][Oo]_[Nn][Aa][Mm][Ee]*

     Default value: "!*"



     3.2.6.10  Variable: FLAGS
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: FLAGS <flag> [<flag> [<flag> ...]]

     Valid values of flag fields.
     For definition of so called "user-flag (",UFLAG" or ",U,FLAG") you
     should include value without comma: "UFLAG". Checker will recognize
     such user flag and will track it in the segment, whether it is given in 
     "UFLAG,UFLAG" format, or "U,FLAG,FLAG".

     You can define up to 30 FLAGS variables. Regular expressions are
     allowed. For "!xx" flag use "!!xx" combination.

     Example of usage: FLAGS CM MO LO
                       FLAGS #01 #02 #08 #09 #18 #20
                       FLAGS !!01 !!02 !!08 !!09 !!18 !!20
                       FLAGS IBN IBN:[0-9] IBN:[1-9][0-9] IBN:[1-9][0-9][0-9] 
                       FLAGS EVY EMA EVY:* EMA:*
                       FLAGS URPK UNPK
                       FLAGS UT[A-X][A-X] UT[A-X][a-x] UT[a-x][A-X] UT[a-x][a-x]


     Default value: "*"


     3.2.6.11  Variable: IMPLIES
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: IMPLIES <flag> = <flag> [<flag> [<flag> ...]]

     Variables IMPLIES allow to define flags, which ØÆ§‡†ß„¨•¢†Ó‚
     inclusion in them some other flags and thus avoid neccessity of
     defining of them in the segment string (eg., flag MNP is implied by
     V42B flag).

     Values of variables IPMLIES form constructions, devided by "equal"
     sign, where in the left part of ‡†¢•≠·‚¢† the flag is defined, which
     includes flag or flags from the right part of ‡†¢•≠·‚¢†.

     You can define up to 30 variables IMPLIES. Regular expressions are
     admitted.

     Examples of usage: IMPLIES V32B = V32
                        IMPLIES V42B = V42 MNP

     Default value: no implies.


     3.2.6.12  Variable: UPPERCASEFLAGS
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: UPPERCASEFLAGS YES | NO

     This variable determines the case (capital or lower case letters),
     admitted for flags in the segment. If UPPERCASEFLAGS=YES, flags in
     lower case are admitted in the segment. Before their processing
     (check for admissibility, check for implition into other flags)
     PNTCHK will uppercase them, so the flags eg. v32b and V32B will be
     identical for the checker. Otherwise (UPPERCASEFLAGS=NO) the flag in
     the lower case will not be admitted.

     Default value: NO


     3.2.7  Settings for autocorrection of errors in segments
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     3.2.7.1  Variable: REMOVEEMPTYLINES
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: REMOVEEMPTYLINES YES | NO

     The variable determines behaviour of the ckecker at detection in a
     segment of empty lines (consisting only from CR/LF (or LF if
     READUNIXLINES is switched on)). If value of the variable is set to
     YES, the empty line (with sending of the appropriate warning to the
     bossnode of the segment) will be removed, but the segment will be
     processed normally; if the value is set to NO the message on a mistake
     will be sent to the bossnode and a segment will not be processed.

     WARNING!!! Watch value of variable EMPTYLINETPL: it should contain
     the reference whether on template with the warning or on template with
     the message on a mistake - depending on value of REMOVEEMPTYLINES.

     Value by default: NO 


     3.2.7.2  Variable: READUNIXLINES
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Switch: READUNIXLINES YES | NO

     Variable READUNIXLINES determines behaviour of the checker at
     detection unix-style lines (not terminating on CR/LF):
     NO - all as earlier, works standard Pascal readln (in the
          DOS/OS2-version a line ending with lf will be not rcognized,
          FPC-versions recognize these lines automatically)
     SILENT - silently process lines as though they come to an end on
          CR/LF (in FPC-versions similarly READUNIXLINES=NO)
     WARNING - to process lines but to give out warning (template
          UNIXLINETPL)
     ERROR - to give out a mistake (template UNIXLINETPL), and reject the
          segment

     WARNING!!! In case of READUNIXLINES=WARNING or ERROR do not overlook
     to correct in appropriate way value of variable UNIXLINETPL: it should
     contain the reference wheter on the template with the warning message or
     on template with the message on a mistake. 

     Value by default: NO


     3.2.7.3  Variable: CHANGEBAUD
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: CHANGEBAUD YES | NO

     Allows to change work of checker in case of detection of a mistake in
     a field "Baud_rate" in a pointsegment line.
     If CHANGEBAUD=YES, erroneous value of a field "Baud_rate" will be
     replaced with the first value of variable BAUD. Thus to the sender
     a warning message is sent, but a segment is considered as correct.
     At CHANGEBAUD=NO the error message is sent and the segmentis considered
     erroneous. 

     The PNTCHK distribution includes example templates baudwrn.tpl and
     bauderr.tpl (defined by BAUDERRORTPL).

     Value by default: NO


     3.2.7.4  Variable: CHANGELOCATION
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: CHANGELOCATION YES | NO

     Allows to change work of checker in case of detection of a mistake in
     a field "Location" in a pointsegment line.
     If CHANGELOCATION=YES, erroneous value of a field "Location" will be
     replaced with the first value of variable BAUD. Thus to the sender
     a warning message is sent, but a segment is considered as correct.
     At CHANGELOCATION=NO the error message is sent and the segmentis considered
     erroneous. 

     The PNTCHK distribution includes example templates
     locatwrn.tpl and locaterr.tpl (defined by LOCATERRORTPL).


     Value by default: NO


     3.2.7.5  Variable: CHANGESYSOP
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: CHANGESYSOP YES | NO | WARN

     Defines scenario for checker operation in case of an invalid value
     in the "System_operator's_name" field.

     CHANGESYSOP=YES: an invalid value in "SysOp" field will be replaced
     with the first value of the SYSOP variable. In this case sender
     will be issued a warning but the segment itself is considered to
     be correct. 
     CHANGESYSOP=NO: an error message is produced and the segment is
     considered to be invalid.
     CHANGESYSOP=WARN: a warning is issued but the segment is processed as
     it is.

     The PNTCHK distribution contains templates sysoperr.tpl, sysopwrn.tpl,
     sysopwr2.tpl (defined in SYSOPERRTPL variable).

     Default option: WARN


     3.2.7.6  Variable: CHANGESYSTEM
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: CHANGESYSTEM YES | NO | WARN

     Defines scenario for checker operation in case of an invalid value
     in the "System_name" field.

     CHANGESYSTEM=YES: an invalid value in "System" field will be replaced
     with the first value of the SYSTEM variable. In this case sender
     will be issued a warning but the segment itself is considered to
     be correct. 
     CHANGESYSTEM=NO: an error message is produced and the segment is
     considered to be invalid.
     CHANGESYSTEM=WARN: a warning is issued but the segment is processed as
     it is.

     The PNTCHK distribution contains templates systerr.tpl, systwrn.tpl,
     systwrn2.tpl (defined in SYSTEMERRTPL variable).

     Default option: WARN


     3.2.7.7  Variable: CHANGEPHONE
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: CHANGEPHONE YES | NO

     Defines scenario for checker operation in case of an invalid value
     in the "Phone" field.
     CHANGEPHONE=YES: an invalid value in "Phone" field will be replaced
     with the first value of the PHONE variable. In this case sender
     will be issued a warning but the segment itself is considered to
     be correct. 
     CHANGEPHONE=NO:  an error message is produced and the segment is
     considered to be invalid.

     The PNTCHK distribution contains example templates phonewrn.tpl and
     phoneerr.tpl (defined in PHONEERRORTPL variable).

     Default option: NO


     3.2.7.8  Variable: REMOVEBADFLAGS
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: REMOVEBADFLAGS YES | NO

     The variable defines if an invalid flag should be removed, issuing
     only a warning message (YES option), instead of an error message (NO
     option) in case of an invalid flag detection.

     Invalid flag definition:
        a) unknown flag (not defined by FLAGS variable in the configuration
           file);
        b) the same flag is detected twice in the same entry;
        c) flag is "implied" by one of the other flags in the entry
           (variables IMPLIES).

     ATTENTION!!!  FLAGERRTPL, IMPLERRTPL and DUPFLGERRTPL should be
     modified appropriately

     Default: NO


     3.2.7.9  Variable: NOFLAG
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: NOFLAG YES | NO | ADD

     The variable defines if the flagless pointlist entries should be
     permitted.
     If NOFLAG=YES the line end with "<baud_rate>," according to the
     standards.
     If NOFLAGD in case of detecting the line an entry with no flags PNTCHK
     will automatically add one flag at the end of the entry. The added flag
     depends on the value of the <baud_rate> field in a give pointlist
     entry according to the default configuration or the values stored
     in ADDEDFLAGS variable.
     If NOFLAG=NO entries with no flags are assumed invalid and the segment
     is not processed.

     ATTENTION!!! NOFLAGERRTPL should be modified appropriately.

     Default: NO



     3.2.7.10  Variable: ADDEDFLAGS
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: ADDEDFLAGS <flag> [<flag> [<flag> ...]]

     This variable defines which flags should be added to the pointlist
     string without any flags. This adding will be done in two cases:

       (1) when the pointsegment string without any flags is being processed
           if the variable NOFLAG is set to ADD;
       (2) if the variable REMOVEBADFLAGS is set to YES and the pointsegment
           string is received containing all incorrect flags. All the incorrect
           flags will be removed and instead of them (if NOFLAG=NO or ADD) a
           flag will be added according with the settings of ADDEDFLAGS.

     The definition of value of this variable is closely connected with
     the variable BAUD. Every flag in the value of this variable is
     ·ÆÆ‚≠Æ·®‚·Ô to the according baudrate in the value if the variable BAUD.

     Eg. when the following values are set:

     BAUD 300 1200 2400 9600
     ADDEDFLAGS V21 V22 V22 V32

     to the pointsegmet string, in which the <baud_rate> field is 300, the
     flag V21 will be added, 1200 and 2400 - V22, 9600 - V32.

     Values by default: V21 §´Ô for 300,
                        V22 for 1200 and 2400,
                        V32 for 9600,
                        MO for any other baud rate.


     3.2.8  External utilities settings
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     3.2.8.1  Variable: EXECBEFORE
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: EXECBEFORE [<path>\]<progname>

     External program to be executed before processing of the segment
     (of each segment in the case of compilation of the pointlist).

     Among the parameters of the external utility one can set:

       %S - the name of the segment being processed (with the path).

     To define the word "%S" itself, you need to insert an extra "%"
     character (%%S).

     Examples of usage: EXECBEFORE c:\util\addcheck.exe %S
                        EXECBEFORE echo.com exec with parameter %%S

     By default the external utility is not executed.


     3.2.8.2  Variable: EXECGOOD
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: EXECGOOD [<path>\]<progname>

     External program to be executed after processing of a correct segment,
     but before sending of the report message and moving the segment into
     the MASTER directory.

     Among the parameters of the external utility one can set:

       %S - the name of the segment being processed (with the path),
       %O - the name of the old segment (the search in the MASTER directory
            will be performed and the name of the first segment, which
            corresponds to the SEGMENTFORMAT definition, will be passed
            to the external utility; if no segment will be found the word
            "%O" itself will be passed).

     To pass the words "%S" and "%O" themselves, you need to insert an
     extra "%" character ("%%S" or "%%O").

     Examples of usage: EXECGOOD c:\util\execgood.exe %S %O
                        EXECGOOD echo.com exec with parameter %%S

     By default the external utility is not executed.


     3.2.8.3  Variable: EXECBAD
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: EXECBAD [<path>\]<progname>

     External program to be executed after processing of an incorrect
     segment, but before sending of the report message and moving the
     segment into the MASTER directory.

     Among the parameters of the external utility one can set:

       %S - the name of the segment being processed (with the path),
       %O - the name of the old segment (the search in the MASTER directory
            will be performed and the name of the first segment, which
            corresponds to the SEGMENTFORMAT definition, will be passed
            to the external utility; if no segment will be found the word
            "%O" itself will be passed).

     To pass the words "%S" and "%O" themselves, you need to insert an
     extra "%" character ("%%S" or "%%O").

     Examples of usage: EXECBAD c:\util\execbad.exe %S %O
                        EXECBAD echo.com exec with parameter %%S

     By default the external utility is not executed.


     3.2.8.4  Variable: TOUCHGOOD
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: TOUCHGOOD [<path>\]<progname>

     This variable defines the name of the flag file created in case of
     receiving and proccessing of a correct segment. The flag file is
     creater just after the execution of the EXECGOOD routine.

     By default the flag file is not created.


     3.2.8.5  Variable: TOUCHBAD
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: TOUCHBAD [<path>\]<progname>

     This variable defines the name of the flag file created in case of
     receiving and proccessing of a correct segment. The flag file is
     creater just after the execution of the EXECGBAD routine.

     By default the flag file is not created.


     3.2.9  Settings for the pointlist compilation (argument "-L")
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     3.2.9.1  Variable: POINTLIST
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: POINTLIST [<path>\]<pntlname>[.<ext>]

     Defines the name of the pointlist being compiled. If defined without
     extention, PNTCHK will add as extention the day-of-year of the
     date of pointlist compilation (or of the nearest friday, according
     to the value of the PNTLDATE variable).

     Examples of usage: POINTLIST c:\pntchk\pntlist\pnt5020
                        POINTLIST pnt5020.ndl

     Default value is impossible.


     3.2.9.2  Variable: PNTLDATE
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: PNTLDATE TODAY | FRIDAY

     The date of the pointlist, inserted into it. This variable
     influences to values of macros @date, @month, @year, @weekday, and
     @daynumber.

     Possible values:

        TODAY  - the date of the pointlist compilation,
        FRIDAY - the date of the nearest friday.

     Default value: TODAY


     3.2.9.3  Variable: FAKECRCSTR
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: FAKECRCSTR <string>

     Variable FAKECRCSTR sets value for @‡ntlcrc which subsequently will
     be replaced with real CRC of the pointlist. The process of definition
     of CRC of the pointlist is the following. As at the moment of its
     assembly it is impossible to determine the CRC, since CRC is calculated
     from already COMPILED pointlist file, fake-character string all over
     again is inserted into the first line of the pointlist. Then, when the
     pointlist is already compiled, its CRC is calculated, and in its
     first line the fake-sequence is substituted by real CRC. By default
     such fake-sequence is '00000', however its value can be changed with
     the help of the definition of variable FAKECRCSTR.

     An example of usage: FAKECRCSTR *****

     Default: 000000


     3.2.9.4  Variable: MAXNUMBER
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: MAXNUMBER <nodenumber>

     Variable MAXNUMBER allows to set biggest number of a node in the
     network. Search of segments is carried out trivially: checker scans
     MASTER directory and tries to find segments of sites under the order,
     since 1, 2, 3 and ending with 32767 then, in case of detection,
     handles these segments. MAXNUMBER allows to limit this process for
     acceleration of the process of assembly.

     An example of usage: MAXNUMBER 1000

     Default: 32767


     3.2.9.5  Variable: CREATIONCHECK
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: CREATIONCHECK FULL | MEDIUM | QUICK

     This variable determines the level of detail of check of incomming
     pointlist segments.

     Possible values:

        FULL   - detailed check of segment (like in '-S' mode),
        MEDIUM - check only for presence in the nodelist and for the
                 age of the segment,
        QUICK  - check only for presence in the nodelist.

     Default value: FULL

     Notice: when MEDIUM/QUICK no copying of the segment to the BACKUPDIR
     directory will be made, even if it is defined.


     3.2.9.6  Variable: EXECPNTLST
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: EXECPNTLST [<path>\]<progname>

     External utility executed after the compilation of the pointlist.

     Among the parameters of the external utility one can set:

       %P - the name of the pointlist compiled,
       %D - day-of-year of the pointlist compiled.

     To pass the words "%P" and "%D" themselves, you need to insert an
     extra "%" character before ("%%P" or "%%D").

     Example of usage: EXECPNTLST c:\util\hatch.exe %P %D

     By default the external utility is not executed.


