     3.2.13  Stuff
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     3.2.13.1  Variable: ASSIGN
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Syntax: ASSIGN @<variable> [@]<value>

     Templates of report-messages, sent by cheker, can include not only
     predefined text, but some macros, which value vill be logged into report
     at the moment of posting.
     The defined number of predefined macros exists, such as, for example,
     @nameprog or @version. Theirs detailed description vill be shown in the
     chapter 4.

     Except of predefined macros user can manually sefine some of such
     variables. ASSIGN variables are used for this. Any macros name can be
     selected, except predefined ones. User`s macros value can be any word or
     group of words, and textfile name.
     In the latter case user`s macros value  must be started with "@" symbol.
     The search of this textfile performs by the rules of template search, e.g.
     default search will be performed in current folder and in folder, defined
     in TEMPLATEPATH variable.

     User can manually define up to 10 macros, using some ASSIGN variables.
     In case of exceed of this number, spare variables will be ignored.

     Examples of use:
                            ASSIGN @HELLO Hello everybody!
                            ASSIGN @NOTE @NOTE.TPL
                            ASSIGN @REPORT @c:\text\report.txt



     3.3  Regular expressions
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     In all configuration files, variables, where operation of compare is used,
     one can define mask, based on regular expressions (regexp - Copyright (c)
     1986 by University of Toronto, written by Henry Spencer).

     Rules of mask definement:

       * - means any number of any characters
       ? - any one symbol or none characters
       [..] (list) - number of symbols, contained in '['...']'.
            Defines one character of list (exmple: [abcde] - any character
            of: a, b, c, d, e).
            If 2 characters from list separated with '-' character, it
            defines the sequence of ASCII characters between them (for
            example, [0-9] defines any decimal digit.
            To include the '[' symbol into the sequence, one should define it
            first (example: []abcde]), '-' symbol should stand first or last.
            The value of combined lists of view [abcd-e] (not [a-cde]) is
            permissiable.


     3.4  ErrorLevels of PNTCHK
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     In depend of error presence in segment(-s), and at originate of emergency
     situation PNTCHK ends it`s work with different errorlevels:

       GoodSegment           = 1 (all segments are good)
       BadSegment            = 2 (all segments are bad)
       DifferentSegment      = 3 (presence of good and bad segments)

     Emergency stop:

       SegmentNotFound            = 201
       IncorrectSegmentName       = 202
       CtlNotFound                = 203
       NetmailNotFound            = 204
       MasterNotFound             = 205
       BadfilesNotFound           = 206
       CannotcreateTempFile       = 207
       CantMove                   = 208
       BackupNotFound             = 209
       TempdirNotFound            = 210
       TemplateNotFound           = 211
       UnableToCreatePointlist    = 212
       NotCompatibleWithLiteMode  = 213


     4.  Macros
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     Templates are widely used in sending report messages, which you can
     edit as you wish, for example, you can translate the template into
     Russian (the example of such translation is uncluded in complete set
     of the product).
     In templates one can define macros to be changed to suitable at this
     moment values for sending report.

     Here is the list of macros:

     General information:

     @NAMEPROG       - software name ("PNTCHK" for DOS version,
                                      "PNTCHK/2" for OS/2 version,
                                      "PNTCHKP" for DOS/32 version,
                                      "PNTCHKW" for Win32 version,
                                      "PNTCHKL" for Linux version,
                                      "PNTCHKB" for FreeBSD version)
     @VERSION        - product version
     @SERIAL         - registraion number (UNREG for unregistered version)
     @OWNER          - product copy owner name
     @ADDRESS        - your system address
     @SENDER         - segment sender's address
     @SEGNAME        - name of processing segment
     @SEGFULLNAME    - full name of segment (with path)
     @NEWSEGNAME     - name of segmet after it's rename
     @SEGLENGTH      - it's length
     @SEGDATE        - time of it's creation
     @SEGLINES       - summary number of lines in segment
     @COMMENTCOUNT   - number of comments in segment
     @SEGFORMAT      - format of the name of segment used
     @NDLNAME        - name of current nodelist
     @NDLFULLNAME    - name of current nodelist with path
     @FIRSTSYSOPNAME - segment sender's name and
     @LASTSYSOPNAME    surname (are taken from nodelist)
     @SEGWRNAGE      - age of segment, at exceeding of which the warning
                       will be shown
     @SEGERRAGE      - age of segment, at exceeding of which the segment
                       won't be processed
     @DAYSTOEXPIRE   - number of days left until the expiration time
     @ERRORNUMBER    - summary number of errors at this moment
     @WARNINGNUMBER  - summary number of warnings at this moment
     @RESULT         - result of the chek - 'Ok' or 'Bad'.


     At line-by-line process of segment:

     @CURRENTSTRING  - current line
     @LINENUMBER     - number of current line
                 it's parts:
     @PREFIX         - prefix
     @POINT          - point's address
     @SYSTEM         - name of the system
     @NEWSYSTEM      - new value of "name of the system" field
     @SYSOP          - SysOp's name
     @NEWSYSOP       - new value of "SysOp's name" field
     @LOCATION       - location
     @NEWLOCATION    - new value of "location" field
     @PHONE          - phone nubmer
     @NEWPHONE       - new phone number at ChangePhone=Yes
     @BAUD           - baudrate of modem
     @NEWBAUD        - new value of "baudrate" field
     @FLAGS          - flags
     @ADDEDFLAG      - added flag at NOFLAG=ADD 

     @IDEALSTRING    - at boss-checking correct line that should be here
     @REASON         - reason of non process of segment at work with nodelist
     @CURRENTFLAG    - currently processed flag at work with flags
     @IMPLTOFLAG     - flag that includes current flag
     @INADMCHAR      - code of found uncommited character at check for
                       inadmissible characters

     At pointlist compilation:

     @DATE           - date
     @MONTH          - month
     @YEAR           - year
     @WEEKDAY        - weekday
     @DAYNUMBER      - number of day in yaer
     @PNTLCRC        - crc16 of created pointlist (can be located only in
                       the 1st line of pointlist

     Macros can be defined in some variables of configuration file, for
     example, variables FROM, SUBJECT, TEARLINE.


     5.  Lite version
     --------------------------------------------------------------------

     PNTCHK can be used not only as coordinator's checking incoming segments
     robot and equiping pointlist robot, but as utility, checking segments
     before sending them to coordinator. For this one should set the
     value of variable LITE to YES.
     At that the value of several variables in the configuration file
     (which are responsible for sending report messages, work with nodelist
     and some other) no longer matter.

     Here is full list of varables, the value of which doesn't influence
     to work of checker in the lite-mode:

     ABSENTPOINTS   EXECGOOD         NODELIST        PVTPOINTS
     AGEERRTPL      FAKECRCSTR       NOFLAGERRTPL    RENAMESEGMENT
     AGEWRNTPL      FLAGERRTPL       NORMALPOINTS    SEGERRAGE
     ASSIGN         FROM             NORMALTEMPLATE  SEGWRNAGE
     ATTRIBUTES     HOLDPOINTS       ONLYONEREPORT   STRERRTPL
     BACKUPDIR      HUBPOINTS        ORIGIN          SUBJECT
     BADFILES       IMPLERRTPL       PHONEERRTPL     SYSOPERRTPL
     BAUDERRTPL     INADMCHARERRTPL  PNTLDATE        SYSTEMERRTPL
     CMNTERRTPL     KILLBAD          PNTLSTERRTPL    TEARLINE
     COORDINATOR    LOCATERRTPL      PNTLSTFOOTER    TEMPDIR
     DOWNPOINTS     MASTER           PNTLSTHEADER    TEMPLATEPATH
     DUPFLGERRTPL   MAXNUMBER        PNTSEGFOOTER    TO
     EMPTYLINETPL   NDLERRTPL        PNTSEGHEADER    TOUCHBAD
     EQNUMERRTPL    NDLINDEX         POINTLIST       TOUCHGOOD
     ERRORTEMPLATE  NETMAIL          PONUMERRTPL     TOUCHSEGMENTS
     EXECBAD        NMBRERRTPL       PREFERRTPL

     PNTCHK distribution contains example configonfig file pnt_lite.ctl, 
     in which all the necessary changes are made.


